The species was first given its scientific name by Temminck in 1824. He placed it in the genus ''Ibis'' but it was separated into the genus ''Inocotis'' created by [[Heinrich Gottlieb Ludwig Reichenbach|Reichenbach]] and this was followed by several major works including the Fauna of British India although the genus ''Pseudibis'' in which [[Brian Houghton Hodgson|Hodgson]] had placed the species had precedence based on the [[Principle of Priority|principle of priority]].<ref>{{cite journal|year=1922| volume=35|title=Inocotis Reichenbach to be replaced by Pseudibis Hodgson|page=79|author=Oberholser, Harry C.|url=https://archive.org/stream/proceedingsofbio35biol#page/78/mode/1up| publisher=[Washington, Biological Society of Washington]| journal=Proceedings of Biology}}</ref> The species included the [[white-shouldered ibis]] as a subspecies ''P. papillosa davisoni'' from 1970s but that is now treated as a full, although closely related species.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club|year=1970|title=Comments on the classification of the Old World Ibises| author=Holyoak, David| pages=67–73|volume=90|issue=3|url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofbritis8990brit#page/66/mode/1up}}</ref> The main morphological difference between the two species is seen in the crown and the upper neck. While ''P. papillosa'' has a patch of red tubercles on the back of the crown, ''P. davisoni'' lacks it. Also, adult ''P. papillosa'' have a narrow, bright red mid-crown that becomes broader on the hindcrown, whereas, adult ''P. davisoni'' has a bare pale blue middle hindcrown that extends to the upper hindneck and forms a complete collar around the upper neck.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Collar J|first1=Nigel|last2=Eames C|first2=Jonathan|title=Head and sex-size dimorphism in Pseudibis papillosa and P.davisoni|journal=BirdingASIA|date=2008|volume=10|page=36|url=http://people.ds.cam.ac.uk/cns26/njc/Papers/Pseudibis.pdf}}</ref> Using nuclear and mitochondrial DNA, the species has been placed within the subfamily Threskiornithinae in a clade that includes both New and Old World members.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Ramirez |first1=J. L. |last2=Miyaki |first2=C. Y. |last3=del Lama |first3=S. N. |date=2013 |title=Molecular phylogeny of Threskionithidae (Aves: Pelecaniformes) based on nuclear and mitochondrial DNA |journal=Genetics and Molecular Research |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=2740–2750|doi=10.4238/2013.July.30.11|doi-broken-date=1 July 2025 |pmid=23979898 }}</ref>
