==Distribution and habitat==
The red-naped ibis is widely distributed in the plains of the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref name=":6" /> In Rajasthan, it is common along the [[Aravalli Range|Aravalli mountains]] but entirely avoids using the trees on the mountains.<ref name=":1" /> The red-naped ibis uses [[lake]]s, [[marsh]]es, riverbeds, irrigated farmlands, dry fallow fields, villages, towns and cities.<ref name="storks" /> More wetlands on the landscape attract a greater number of red-naped ibises, but birds forage largely in dry fields increasing use of wetlands for foraging during summer.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> In semi-arid areas, it is commonly seen in small flocks of 2–4, which could be family groups, with larger groups being relatively rare.<ref name=":3">{{Cite journal |last1=Ameta |first1=Hitesh |last2=Koli |first2=Vijay Kumar |last3=Kittur |first3=Swati |last4=Sundar |first4=K. S. Gopi |date=2022 |title=Is the Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa a "waterbird"? Distribution, abundance and habitat use in landscapes with two different dominant land uses in Udaipur district, Rajasthan, India |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Ametaetal_RNI_Udaipur_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=30–39}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite journal |last1=Asawra |first1=Krishna |last2=Mitra |first2=Anshuk |last3=Mehta |first3=Kanishka |last4=Koli |first4=Vijay Kumar |last5=Sundar |first5=K. S. Gopi |date=2022 |title=Effect of wetland extent on seasonal abundance and behaviour of Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa in the semi-arid Dungarpur district, Rajasthan, India |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Asawra_etal_RNI_Dungarpur_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=60–68}}</ref> Fewer ibises were counted in wetter locations and seasons.<ref name=":6">{{Cite journal |last1=Kittur |first1=Swati |last2=Sundar |first2=K. S. Gopi |date=2022 |title=Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa density across time and space in south Asian farmlands: the influence of location, season, and rainfall |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022KitturSundar_RNIAcrossSpaceTime_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=69–77}}</ref>

It is a common breeding resident in [[Haryana]], [[Punjab]], Rajasthan and the Gangetic plains. It extends into southern India but is not found in the forested regions or the arid zone of the extreme southeast of the peninsula or Sri Lanka.<ref name="hbk" /> In lowland Nepal, most foraging red-naped ibis were seen in agricultural fields, but most nests were seen in forests.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Katuwal |first1=Hem Bahadur |last2=Quan |first2=Rui-Chang |date=2022 |title=Status of the Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa in agricultural landscapes of Nepal |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022KatuwalQuan_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=24–29}}</ref> Red-naped ibis commonly use villages, towns and mega-cities seeking food, nesting and roosting.<ref name="storks" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4" /><ref name=":7" /><ref name=":11" />

The red-naped ibis is largely [[Diurnality|diurnal]] in its foraging and other activities,<ref>{{cite web |title=Indian black ibis / Oriental black ibis / Red naped ibis (Pseudibis papillosa Temminck) |url=http://www.ibisring.org/article/indian-black-ibis |website=Ibisring}}</ref> at night roosting communally on trees or on islands.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=storks/> Nocturnal activities such as loud calling is rare.<ref name=":9" /> In semi-arid areas, they avoid potential competitive interactions with other sympatric ibis species by foraging largely in upland habitats.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Ameta |first1=Hitesh |last2=Koli |first2=Vijay Kumar |last3=Sundar |first3=K. S. Gopi |date=2024 |title=Is Three a Crowd? Three Indian Ibis Species Vary Strategies to Achieve Sympatry Depending on Different Seasons, Landscapes and Habitats |url=https://bioone.org/journals/waterbirds/volume-47/issue-1/063.047.0109/Is-Three-a-Crowd-Three-Indian-Ibis-Species-Vary-Strategies/10.1675/063.047.0109.full |journal=Waterbirds |volume=47 |issue=1 |doi=10.1675/063.047.0109 |issn=1524-4695|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

==Food and foraging==
[[File:Red-naped ibis (Pseudibis papillosa) immature.jpg|thumb|A juvenile]]
Early observers and investigations of stomach contents showed their diet to include crustaceans (prawns, crabs), insects (beetles, grasshoppers, crickets), scorpions, carrion and frogs.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jerdon |first=T. C. |title=Birds of India: A natural history. Volume III. |date=1864 |publisher=Wyman and Co., Calcutta, India. |pages=769–770}}</ref><ref name=":10" /> Subsequent additional observations have shown the red-naped ibis to be more omnivorous, feeding on carrion,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Khan |first=Asif N. |date=2015 |title=Indian Black Ibis Pseudibis papillosa feeding on carrion |journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |language=en |volume=112 |issue=1 |page=28 |doi=10.17087/jbnhs/2015/v112i1/92323 |issn=0006-6982 |doi-access=free}}</ref> insects, frogs, other small vertebrates, and grain.<ref name=hbk /> They forage mainly in dry open land and stubbly fields, sometimes joining egrets and other birds on land being tilled to feed on exposed earthworms, disturbed insects and dig for beetle grubs.<ref name=":4">{{Cite journal |last1=Charan |first1=Manish Singh |last2=Sharma |first2=Pradeep |last3=Singh |first3=Mahindra |last4=Kittur |first4=Swati |last5=Sundar |first5=K. S. Gopi |date=2022 |title=Natural history and behavioural observations of Red-naped ibis Pseudibis papillosa in Dhariawad and Sikar cities, Rajasthan |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Charanetal_RNINaturalHistory_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=55–59}}</ref> They walk and like other tactile-feeding ibises, probe in the soft ground. The rarely wade in water<ref name=fbi2 /> but have been observed seeking out frogs hiding in crab holes.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Johnson, J. Mangalraj|title=Black ibis Pseudibis papillosa feeding on frogs from crab holes|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |year=2003|volume=100|issue=1|pages= 111–112|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48602685}}</ref> They feed commonly at garbage dumps eating mammal and bird carcasses.<ref name=pcr /><ref name=":4" /> In small towns, red-naped ibis hunt adult Rock Pigeons and predate their eggs from nests on buildings.<ref name=":4" /> Near towns, ibises ate road kills and pulled out marrow of bones of cattle dead from collisions with traffic.<ref name=":4" /> During droughts they were seen feeding on carrion and insect larvae that were feeding on meat. They also feed on groundnut and other crops. In British India, indigo planters considered them useful as they appeared to consume a large number of [[Cricket (insect)|crickets]] in the fields earning them the moniker "planter's friend".<ref name=":0">{{cite journal|title=The birds of the Madhubani sub-division of the Darbhanga district, Tirhut, with notes on species noticed elsewhere in the district. Part 6|author=Inglis, C.M.|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=15|issue=1|pages=70–77|year=1903|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2096481}}</ref><ref name=":10">{{cite book|title=The food of birds in India.|author=Mason, C.W.|editor=Maxwell-Lefroy, H.|publisher=Imperial Department of Agriculture in India|url=https://archive.org/stream/foodofbirdsinind00masorich#page/280/mode/2up/|pages=280–280–282|year=1911}}</ref> Adult and juveniles birds in Delhi dig into flowers of ''[[Bombax ceiba]]'' seemingly drinking nectar.<ref name=":7">{{Cite journal |last=Sinha |first=N. |date=2022 |title=Nectar in the diet of the Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Sinha_RNINectarDrinking_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=78–81}}</ref> Fishing by red-naped ibis is rare and has been observed in reservoirs.<ref name=":4" />

Ibises roost in groups and fly to and from the regularly used roost site in "V" formation.<ref name=whistler>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n545/mode/2up|pages=497–498| title=Popular Handbook of Indian Birds|edition=4th| author=Whistler, Hugh| year=1949| publisher=Gurney and Jackson|place=London}}</ref>

==Breeding==
{{birdsong|url=https://xeno-canto.org/species/Pseudibis-papillosa |species=Red-naped ibis}}
Red-naped ibises usually nest individually and not in mixed species heronries. There are a few observations of colonial breeding by red-naped ibis. A small colony of 3-5 nests was reported from Sind, Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Baker |first=E. C. S. |title=The nidification of birds of the Indian empire Pandionidae-Podicepidae. Vol IV. |date=1935 |publisher=Taylor & Francis, London, UK}}</ref> Two nests on a single tree was observed in Nepal.<ref name="storks" /> Two pairs were seen nesting on Palmyra palms (''Borassus flabellifer'') in an institutional campus in Andhra Pradesh.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sangha |first=H. S. |date=2013 |title=Nesting of Black Ibis Pseudibis papillosa on electricity pylons near Bikaner, Rajasthan |journal=Indian Birds |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=10–11}}</ref> A small but expanding colony of 20 nests spread over two large trees in a village is being monitored in Gujarat.<ref name=":11">{{Cite journal |last=Tere |first=A. |date=2022 |title=Observations of colonially-nesting Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa at Amla, Gujarat: nest tree preference and breeding success |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Tere_ColonialNestingRNI_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=40–47}}</ref> In some towns, cities and agricultural areas with few trees, red-naped ibis built most nests on artificial structures such as electricity pillion towers, cell phone towers, and light poles.<ref name=":5">{{Cite journal |last=Juvvadi |first=Pranay S. |date=2022 |title=Nesting substrates of Red-Naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa in human dominated landscapes of Telangana, India |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022Juvvadi_RNI_Telangana_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=48–54}}</ref><ref name=":4" /> The habit of using artificial structures for nesting was not observed in studies conducted in the 1990s and seems to be recently learnt, but has been observed widely in Gujarat, Telangana and Rajasthan.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ali, A.H.M.S. |author2=Kumar, Ramesh |author3=Arun, P.R. |year=2013 |title=Black ibis ''Pseudibis papillosa'' nesting on power transmission line pylons, Gujarat, India |journal=BirdingAsia |volume=19 |pages=104–106}}</ref><ref name=":5" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Ali |first1=M. S. |last2=Kumar |first2=S. R. |last3=Arun |first3=P. R. |date=2013 |title=Black Ibis Pseudibis papillosa nesting on power transmission line pylons, Gujarat, India |journal=BirdingAsia |volume=19 |pages=104–106}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite journal |last1=Tiwary |first1=Nawin |last2=Sundar |first2=K. S. Gopi |date=2022 |title=Special Section Editorial: Spotlight on the Red-naped Ibis Pseudibis papillosa |url=https://storkibisspoonbill.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/2022SpecialSectionEdit_TiwarySundar_Final.pdf |journal=SIS Conservation |volume=4 |pages=15–23}}</ref>

The breeding season is variable but most often between March and October and tending to precede the monsoons. When pair-bonding, females beg for food from the males at foraging grounds. Males also trumpet from the nest site.<ref name="storks">{{cite book|pages=241–244| title=Storks, ibises and spoonbills of the world|author1=Hancock, James A.| author2=Kushlan, James A.| author3=Kahl, M.Philip|publisher=Academic Press| year=1992}}</ref> The nests are mainly large stick platforms that are 35-60 cm in diameter and about 10-15 cm deep. Old nests are reused as are those of kites and vultures. The nests are loosely lined with straw and fresh material to the nest is added even when the eggs are being incubated. The nests are usually at a height of 6–12 metres above ground, on banyan (''[[Ficus benghalensis]]'') or peepal (''[[Ficus religiosa]]'') trees, often close to human habitation. Ibis pairs copulate mainly when perched on trees.<ref name="storks" /> The eggs are 2–4 in number and pale bluish green in colour. They are sparsely flecked and have pale reddish blotches. Both male and female red-naped ibis incubate the eggs which hatch after 33 days.<ref name="hbk">{{cite book|last1=Ali|first1=Salim|last2=Ripley|first2=S. Dillon|title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan|year=1978|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New Delhi|edition=2nd|pages=112–113}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Salimkumar, C.|author2=Soni, V.C. |year=1984| title= Laboratory observations on the incubation period of the Indian Black Ibis ''Pseudibis papillosa'' (Temminck)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=81|issue=1|pages=189–191|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48874097}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The nest and eggs of Indian Birds. Volume 3.|edition=2nd|author=Hume, A.O.|year=1890|publisher=R.H. Porter|place=London|pages=228–231| url=https://archive.org/stream/nestseggsofindia03humerich#page/228/mode/2up/}}</ref> Several pairs nested within city limits in Udaipur preferring to nest on ''Azadirachta indica'' (a tree species native to India, but introduced to Udaipur city), ''Eucalyptus'' sp. (an introduced tree species to India) and ''Ficus religiosa'' (a native tree protected by religious beliefs in India).<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal |last1=Mehta |first1=Kanishka |last2=Koli |first2=Vijay K. |last3=Kittur |first3=Swati |last4=Sundar |first4=K. S. Gopi |date=2024 |title=Can you nest where you roost? Waterbirds use different sites but similar cues to locate roosting and breeding sites in a small Indian city |journal=Urban Ecosystems |volume=27|issue=4 |pages=1279–1290 |doi=10.1007/s11252-023-01454-5 |bibcode=2024UrbEc..27.1279M }}</ref> After successful fledging of chicks, Red-naped ibis nests were taken over by pairs of Red-necked Falcons (''Falco chicquera'') in Surendranagar district, Gujarat.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bhatt |first=Nirav |date=2022 |title=Reproductive Rate of the Red-Headed Falcon (Falco chicquera) in Surendranagar District, Gujarat, India |journal=Journal of Raptor Research |volume=57 |issue=1 |pages=75–80 |doi=10.3356/JRR-21-73 |issn=0892-1016}}</ref> In Telangana, an old nest of red-naped ibis was used by Red-necked Falcon above which was an active nest of red-naped ibis, both located on electricity pillion tower.<ref name=":5" />

== Parasites ==
The nematode ''Belanisakis ibidis'' has been identified from the small intestines of the species<ref>{{cite journal|title=On some nematodes from Indian vertebrates. I. Birds|author=Inglis, William G.|doi=10.1080/00222935408651795|journal= Annals and Magazine of Natural History|series=12|volume=7|issue=83|year=1954|pages=821–826}}</ref> while the feathers of ibises are host to specific species of bird lice in the genus ''Ibidoecus''. The species found in the red-naped ibis is ''Ibdidoecus dennelli''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Tandan, B.K.|journal=Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London|year=1958|volume=110|issue=14|pages=393–410|title=Mallophagan parasites from Indian birds-Part V. Species belonging to the genus ''Ibidoecus'' Cummings, 1916 (Ischnocera)|url=http://darwin.biology.utah.edu/PubsHTML/LicePubPages/LicePDF%27s/1958/Tandan1958.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2311.1958.tb00379.x|archive-date=2011-11-11|access-date=2015-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111024407/http://darwin.biology.utah.edu/PubsHTML/LicePubPages/LicePDF%27s/1958/Tandan1958.pdf}}</ref> ''Patagifer chandrapuri'', a species of [[Digenea]] flatworm has been found in the intestines of specimens from Allahabad.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A revision of Patagifer Dietz, 1909 (Digenea: Echinostomatidae) and a key to its species|author1=Faltynkova, Anna|author2= Gibson, David I. | author3= Kostadinova, Aneta| year=2008| journal=Systematic Parasitology|volume =70|issue=3| pages=159–183 | doi=10.1007/s11230-008-9136-8|pmid=18535788 |s2cid=20578624 }}</ref> In captivity, a trematode ''Diplostomum ardeiformium'' has been described from a red-naped ibis host.<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Zeitschrift für Parasitenkunde | volume=21| issue=5|pages=381–425| title=Trematoden aus indischen Vögeln des Berliner Tierparks| author=Odening, Klaus|doi=10.1007/BF00260995|year = 1962| s2cid=9506473| language=de}}</ref> Protist parasites include ''Eimeria''-like organisms.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Chauhan P. P. S, Bhatia B. B. | year = 1970 | title = Eimerian oozysts from Pseudibis papillosa | journal = Indian Journal of Microbiology | volume = 10 | issue = 2| pages = 53–54 }}</ref>

== In culture ==
[[File:BlackibisDSC_6311_090913_pusa.jpg|thumb|An adult in flight]]
The Tamil [[Sangam literature]] mentions a bird called the "''anril''" which was described as having a curved bill and calling from atop palmyra palms (''[[Borassus flabellifer]]''). [[Madhaviah Krishnan]] identified the bird positively as the black ibis and ruled out contemporary suggestions that this was a [[sarus crane]]. He based his identification on a line that mentions the arrival of {{not a typo|''anrils''}} at dusk and calling from atop palmyra palms. He also pointed out ibises to locals and asked them for the name and noted that a few did refer to it as {{not a typo|''anrils''}}. Sangam poetry also mentions that the birds mated for life and always walked about in pairs, one of the leading reasons for others to assume that this was the sarus crane, a species that is not found in southern India.<ref>Krishnan, M. (1986) The Anril. Reprinted without source details in ''Nature's Spokesman'' (2000) edited by Ramachandra Guha. Oxford University Press. pp. 93-95.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/TreatmentNatureInSangamLiterature/Treatment%20nature%20in%20Sangam%20literature#page/n281/mode/2up|author=Varadarajan, Munuswamy |year=1957| title= The Treatment of Nature in Sangam Literature| publisher= The South India Saiva Siddhanta Works Publishing Society|place= Tirunelveli|page=260}}</ref>

A number of names in Sanskrit literature including "kālakaṇṭak" have been identified as referring to this species.<ref>{{cite book|author=Dave, K.N.| title=Birds in Sanskrit literature|year=1985| publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|place=New Delhi|page=384}}</ref> Jerdon noted the local names of "karankal" and "nella kankanam" in Telugu and "buza" or "kālā buza" in Hindi.<ref name=jerdon>{{Cite book|title=The birds of India. Volume 3 |year=1864| publisher=George Wyman and Co.|place= Calcutta |pages=769–770|url= https://archive.org/stream/birdsofindiabein03jerd#page/768/mode/2up}}</ref>

In British India, sportsmen referred to the species as the "king curlew",<ref>{{cite book|author=Le Messurier, A.|year=1904| title=Game, Shore, and Water Birds of India. |publisher=W. Thacker and Co.|place=London|edition=4th|url=https://archive.org/stream/gamesshoreandwat029723mbp#page/n191/mode/2up/|pages=183–184}}</ref> "king ibis" or "black curlew"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dewar, Douglas| year=1920| publisher=John Lane|place=London|title=Indian Birds being a key to the common birds of the plains of India.|url= https://archive.org/stream/indianbirdsbeing00dewa#page/217/mode/1up/|page=217}}</ref> and it was considered good eating as well as sport for falconers (using the [[Shaheen falcon]]).<ref name=jerdon /> They would race and soar to escape falcons.<ref>{{cite book|author=Burton, Richard F. |year=1852| title= Falconry in the valley of the Indus|place= London|publisher= John Van Voorst| url=https://archive.org/stream/falconryinvalle01burtgoog#page/n83/mode/2up/s|pages=57–58}}</ref> Cultivators referred to the species as "planter's friend" based on the large number of crickets the ibises consumed on indigo plantations.<ref name=":0" />

== Status and conservation ==
[[File:Red Naped Ibis 4.jpg|thumb|A pair of Red Naped Ibises at [[Mehtab Bagh]], [[Agra]]]]
The species has declined greatly in [[Pakistan]] due to hunting and habitat loss. The species has been largely unaffected in India and they are traditionally tolerated by farmers and people in cities.<ref name="kushlan">{{cite book |author1=Hancock, James |title=Storks, Ibises and Spoonbills of the World |author2=Kushlan, James A. |author3=Kahl, M. Philip |publisher=A&C Black |year=2010 |pages=241–244}}</ref><ref name=":1" /> DDT levels in blood plasma was 19 ng/mL in red-naped ibis - the lowest among 13 bird species sampled in a project in India.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Dhananjayan |first1=Venugopal |last2=Muralidharan |first2=Subramanian |date=2010 |title=Levels of Organochlorine Pesticide Residues in Blood Plasma of Various Species of Birds from India |journal=Bulletin of Environmental Contamination and Toxicology |language=en |volume=85 |issue=2 |pages=129–136 |doi=10.1007/s00128-010-0045-6 |pmid=20571760 |bibcode=2010BuECT..85..129D |issn=1432-0800}}</ref>

Estimates of population density of red-naped are mostly derived from volunteer counts at wetlands. These estimates are not useful since the majority of red-naped ibis populations use upland and more dry habitats.<ref name=":6" /> The only robust field-based monitoring exercise for the species conservatively provides the population estimate at 20,81,800 (95% CI: 17,45,340 - 25,41,460), and this makes the red-naped ibis among the most populous endemic waterbird species anywhere.<ref name=":6" /> The widely varying seasonal numbers of the species makes it a challenging species to monitor. Though most ibises forage in upland and other dry habitats, more of them occur in places with more wetlands on the landscape.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> Red-naped ibis do not appear to have preferences for particular sized wetlands, thought having a few large wetlands on the landscape benefits populations in semi-arid areas where all the smaller wetlands dry up in the summer.<ref name=":2" />

Studies in urban areas are showing the ability of Red-naped ibis to exploit city-based foods, and nest on artificial structures such as lighting poles even if these are located in busy marketplaces.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":7" /> Red-naped ibises may be benefitting from expanding urban areas as long as urban greening continues to provide them with nesting trees, especially in arid and semi-arid areas where tall trees for nesting are sparse on the countryside, and people continue not to persecute the birds.<ref name=":1" /> Expanding cereal agriculture has led to decline of trees across large areas, but red-naped ibis continue to proliferate in such areas using artificial nesting substrates such as electricity powerline towers and cell phone towers.<ref name=":5" /> The studies collectively suggest that the red-naped ibis may be increasing in numbers due to their behavioural plasticity, especially their ability to use a range of human-modified habitats and areas.<ref name=":8" />

A few zoos including the ones at Frankfurt, Singapore (Jurong park) have successfully bred the species in captivity. An individual lived in captivity at Berlin zoo for 30 years.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Brouwer, Koen| author2=Schifter, Herbert|author3=Jones, Marvin L.| title=Longevity and breeding records of ibises and spoonbills in captivity| journal=International Zoo Yearbook |year=1994| volume=33| pages=94–102 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-1090.1994.tb03561.x }}</ref>

